<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-154-372  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 154 372.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Feb 12 1990 v11 n7 p1(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mobile networks keep transportation rolling.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Conlon, Theresa.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Companies are installing wireless mobile data networks to keeptrack of its mobile assets, its trucks, railcars and cargo shipswith freight.andP;  A fixed computer transmits data to nearly anymoving vehicle via satellite, meteor burst communications or radiofrequency technologies.andP;  Networks can track vehicles, keeping themup to date with customer demands and inquiries, with accurateinformation about shipments.andP;  Carriers are giving rise to a newtechnology called Automatic Equipment Identification (AEI) thatcompanies are trying to make a standard.andP;  AEI technology uses amicrochip-based radio frequency tag that is put on the vehicle.andO;An antenna or scanning device can read information from the chipand send it to an inventory management system computer givingshipping and vehicle information.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TransportationPortable TerminalsNetworksRemote AccessInventory ControlWireless Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Mobile communications companies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>